subSubSection.paragraph:
Pedipalps :
Femur with DI, DE and VI carinae well developed ( Fig. 13F ), granular, extending the entire length of the segment, with two DE macrosetae; anterior margin with few scattered large granules and two macrosetae; rest of the intercarinal surfaces smooth. Patella, DI and VI carinae formed by a few scattered granules, remaining surfaces smooth, ( Figs. 13 G, H ); with two DI and two VI macrosetae. Chela manus ( Figs. 13 A–E) slender, length/ width ratio, males: 3.44–4.38 (N=5; mean=3.85), females: 4.40–4.76 (N=2); length/height, males: 2.88–3.48 (N=5; mean=3.26); females: 3.38–3.61 (N=2); with a blunt VM accessory carina, internal surface with slight bulge near articulation of movable finger (females) ( Fig. 13E ), or with a pronounced, subtriangular projection (males) ( Fig. 13A ); fingers elongated, with a median row of denticles, and five or six pairs of accessory denticles, the basal external denticle is usually part of the median row. Trichobothrial pattern neobothriotaxic major Type C, with one accessory trichobothrium in V series of chela; femur with 3 trichobothria ( d , i , e ), one macroseta (M1) between with d and i ; patella with 19 trichobothria (2 d , i , 3 et , est , 2 em , 2 esb , 5 eb ,
3 V
), with esb 2 petite; chela with 27 trichobothria ( Dt , Db , 5 Et , Est , Esb , 3 Eb , dt , dst , dsb , db , et , est , esb , eb , ib , it ,
5 V
), with Et 4 petite, Esb forming triangle with Eb 2 and Eb 3 .

